Describe the catabolism of heme, including the sites in which reactions occur, and the colour of the intermediates 

At the spleen, hemoglobin is broken down into heme and globin. Globin is broken down into amino acids, which are recycled for protein synthesis. Heme is converted to green biliverdin and Fe2+ at the spleen. Biliverdin is converted to unconjugated bilirubin, which is then transported through blood to the liver via albumin. This bilirubin is then conjugated with glucuronic acid in the liver. Conjugated bilirubin is secreted by hepatocytes into biliary ducts (with bile) then into the intestine, where it is unconjugated, then converted to urobilinogen (colourless) by intestinal bacteria. Urobilinogen is then oxidised either to yellow urobilin at the kidney to be excreted via urine, or to brown stercobilin (intestinal bacteria) and excreted in feces. Note that some urobilinogen is reabsorbed from the gut and enters portal blood, participating in the enterohepatic urobilinogen cycle.  

 

Describe the cellular mechanisms for the hepatic uptake, conjugation and secretion of bile salts and bilirubin 

Primary bile acids are synthesised by hepatocytes. Bile acids are then conjugated with either glycine or taurine amino acids (8 possible conjugated bile acids). Conjugated bile acids are known as bile salts. They are then secreted by the hepatocytes into the biliary ducts. When these bile salts reach the lumen of the intestine, bacteria remove the amino acid groups to deconjugate the bile salts back to (secondary) bile acids. These are taken up by transporters at the terminal ileum, and return to the liver by blood for further secretion.  

 

RBCs break down into heme + globin. The conversion of heme to biliverdin then to bilirubin occurs in macrophages (tissue macrophages, the spleen, or the liver), and bilirubin is taken up via facilitated diffusion at the liver. It is then conjugated with glucuronic acid, then secreted via bile into intestine.  

 

Describe the fate of bilirubin once it has reached the GIT 

Unconjugated -> converted to urobilinogen -> converted to yellow urobilin at kidney or converted to brown stercobilin or enters enterohepatic urobilinogen cycle 

 

Describe the structure of cholesterol and its functional roles in the body 

Cholesterol is used in the cell phospholipid bilayer membrane for permeability and fluidity, in vitamin D synthesis, in the manufacture of bile salts, and in steroid hormone synthesis.  

 

Structure: 

4 linked hydrocarbon rings forming a steroid structure, with a hydrocarbon tail at one end and a hydroxyl group at the other end. It has one carbon double bond.  

 

Describe the dietary sources and synthesis of cholesterol 

Cholesterol can be found largely in animal fat in meat, eggs, and dairy products. 

 

Synthesis of cholesterol 

 

 

Acetyl CoA is formed from glucose, fatty acids and amino acids. Note that one mevalonic acid produces one isopentenyl pyrophosphate. 6 isopentenyl pyrophosphates are required to from one squalene. Increased levels of intercellular cholesterol inhibits synthesis, whilst decreased levels of intercellular cholesterol stimulates synthesis. 80% of cholesterol synthesis occurs in the liver, whilst 20% occurs in peripheral tissue intestine, adrenals, brain, etc.  

 

Cholesterol metabolism 

The liver synthesises the majority of cholesterol from acetate. Cholesterol is also received from extra-hepatic tissues. Cholesterol is excreted into bile either simply as cholesterol, or as bile acids after metabolism has occurred. In addition to the enterohepatic cycle of bile acids, cholesterol is also reabsorbed in the intestines (50%). The rest is excreted.  

 

Describe the formation of bile acids from cholesterol 

Bile acid synthesis occurs in hepatocytes via cytochrome-P450 mediated oxidation of cholesterol in a multi-step process.  

 

Describe the transport of lipids in blood, including the role of the liver 

Free cholesterols and triglycerides are both insoluble in water, and are instead transported in lipoproteins. Plasma cholesterol in lipoproteins are usually in the form of cholesteryl ester.  

 

Structure of lipoproteins 

Lipoproteins have a phospholipid monolayer with cholesterol and apolipoproteins embedded in it. The core of the lipoprotein contains triglycerides and cholesteryl esters. 

  

 

 

Triglyceride-rich chylomicrons from the intestine and z from liver are brought into blood. In the capillaries, free fatty acids are produced due to metabolism of the lipoproteins which are absorbed by body tissue. The blood then delivers chylomicron remnants, VLDL remnants and some LDLs back to the liver. From the body tissue, cholesterol is transported back to the liver by HDL precursors from the liver and intestine, as HDL.  

 

 

 

 

 

Briefly describe the classes of lipoproteins and the general role of each 

Lipoproteins are classified by density. Good lipoproteins are HDLs, and bad lipoproteins include LDLs, IDLs and VLDLs. Note than a chylomicron or chylomicron remnant is bigger than a VLDL in size.  

 

 

Apolipoproteins are crucial as they serve as a ligand for lipoprotein receptors.  

 

Important apolipoprotein:  

ApoA-I is a major protein of HDL, activates LCAT to convert cholesterol to cholesteryl ester, reduces risk of heart failure 

ApoB-100 is a major protein of LDL, binds to LDL receptors for LDL-R mediated endocytosis by an extrahepatic cell, increases risk of heart failure 

ApoC-II activates lipoprotein lipase (LPL) 

 

Dynamic nature of lipid transport 

-In circulation, cholesterol, triglycerides and phospholipids can be exchanged between circulating lipoprotein classes via a transfer protein.  

-Triglycerides in circulating lipoproteins can be metabolised by lipases in capillary endothelial cells into free fatty acids and glycerol for tissue uptake, eg by lipoprotein lipase and hepatic lipase 

-Chemical modifications occur during transport in blood, eg oxidation, glycation of apolipoproteins 

 

Hence, there is significant modification of lipoproteins which impacts their particle properties.

Why HDLs are so good 

HDLs are vehicles for reverse cholesterol transport. They help remove excess free cholesterol from peripheral tissue depots, returning it back to the liver for processing. At the liver, cholesterol is either converted to bile salt or excreted into bile. Remember that 50% of cholesterol in intestines are excreted. This ability for HDL to remove cholesterol from lipid-laden macrophages in arterial walls is termed Cholesterol Efflux Capacity. For this reason, HDLs have anti-atherogenic properties.
